Final Plots and Summary

Density Plot of Loan Amount by Income Range

This plot shows the Loan Amount of differing Income ranges. I think that this plot shows the habits or various Loanees well as you can understand that that with a lower income may use small loans to pay for things like bills or unexpected accidents, as they may not have much saved to cover these costs. It also shows the general borrowing habits of higher earnings, who cannot only borrow more, but may be likely to be using the resulting loan to purchase more expensive goods. The reason that we are showing the difference in borrowing habits by Income Range and we can see if these were linked.

Monthly Income vs Loan Payment in Washington, D.C.

This graph combines two that we saw earlier buy looks at Washington, D.C. instead. It gives more information about the Prosper rating and income range vs Monthly Payments and Income. We can see the same trend of lower incomes typically being bunched closer together with the higher earners having a lot more variation in terms of the Income vs Payments. It is also not neccesarily the case the more you earn the higher your rating. After looking at income data above it was helpful for us to see this information plotted again but now looking at the Income vs Loan Payment data.

Credit Score vs Loan Amount in Washington, D.C.

This chart takes another look at the Income and Prosper Rating in D.C. but now we are looking at the relationship to the lower range of the Credit Rating. We can see from this graph that the Prosper Rating is lower for those with a lower credit score, as we would expect, but we can also see that there are those with small loan amounts and scores around 700 that also have a low rating. The reasoning behind choosing this plot was to enable us to see if the Prosper rating was liable to correlate to certain loan amounts.
